  "text": "The v38 dashboard schema migration bug is located in the Grafana repository (grafana--26d36ec) under apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/.\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe bug is in `apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/v38.go`, in the function `processPanelsV38`. The migration converts table panel `displayMode` strings to the structured `cellOptions` format. It must handle two separate concerns:\n1. Migrating `fieldConfig.defaults.custom.displayMode` → `fieldConfig.defaults.custom.cellOptions`\n2. Migrating `fieldConfig.overrides[*].properties[*]` entries with `id: \"custom.displayMode\"` → `id: \"custom.cellOptions\"`\n\nThe flawed conditional logic is the nested guard:\n\n```go\nif defaults, ok := fieldConfig[\"defaults\"].(map[string]interface{}); ok {\n    if custom, ok := defaults[\"custom\"].(map[string]interface{}); ok {\n        // migrate defaults.custom.displayMode ...\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn the original buggy form of this code, the call to `migrateOverrides(fieldConfig)` was placed **inside** the outer `if defaults` block (or even inside the inner `if custom` block). This meant that when a table panel had `fieldConfig.defaults` but **no** `custom` sub-object (a common real-world case where column widths and text alignment are set only via field overrides, not via defaults), the `migrateOverrides` call was never reached. As a result, override entries with `id: \"custom.displayMode\"` were silently left unmigrated — they were not converted to `id: \"custom.cellOptions\"` — causing the Grafana table panel to lose all per-column display configuration (widths, alignment, cell rendering modes) after import.\n\nThe fix is to call `migrateOverrides(fieldConfig)` **unconditionally**, outside both `if defaults` and `if custom` blocks, so that overrides are always migrated regardless of whether `fieldConfig.defaults.custom` exists. The current code in the repository includes a comment documenting this requirement:\n\n```go\n// Update any overrides referencing the cell display mode\n// This must be called regardless of whether defaults.custom exists\nmigrateOverrides(fieldConfig)\n```\n\nThe test case `\"table with missing defaults.custom but overrides with custom.displayMode\"` in `v38_test.go` directly exercises this scenario: a table panel with `\"defaults\": {}` (no `custom` key) but with overrides containing `custom.displayMode` entries. The expected output shows those overrides must be migrated to `custom.cellOptions` even though `defaults.custom` is absent.\n\n## Schema Version Registration\n\nThe schema version constant file is `apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/migrations.go`. It defines `LATEST_VERSION = 42` and registers V38 in the `GetMigrations` map:\n\n```go\n38: V38,\n```\n\nThis is the authoritative registry that wires the V38 migration function into the migration pipeline executed by `apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/migrate.go`.\n\n## Summary of Affected Files\n\n- **`apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/v38.go`**: Contains `V38` (entry point), `processPanelsV38` (the function with the flawed conditional — the nested `if defaults` / `if custom` guard that caused `migrateOverrides` to be skipped when `defaults.custom` was absent), and `migrateOverrides` (the helper that migrates override properties).\n- **`apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/migrations.go`**: The schema version constant file that registers `38: V38` in `GetMigrations` and defines `LATEST_VERSION`."
}

